# React Best Practices

- Use functional components and hooks only; no class components in new code.
- Keep components single-purpose; extract subcomponents before complexity grows.
- Derive state when possible; avoid duplicating source-of-truth data.
- Use controlled side effects: each `useEffect` has a clear external sync purpose.
- Include complete dependency arrays; do not disable hook lint rules casually.
- Memoize only when profiling or clear render pressure justifies it.
- Keep props typed explicitly; avoid massive prop bags and hidden contracts.
- Lift state only as high as needed; prefer local state by default.
- Co-locate feature logic with components, then extract reusable hooks intentionally.
- Ensure accessible semantics: labels, keyboard behavior, focus states, and ARIA.

# Layered structure

## Naming Conventions

- All file and folder names must be `kebab-case` (lowercase only). Never use PascalCase or camelCase for filenames.
- Component symbols: PascalCase → `UserProfile`
- Hook files: `use-<name>.ts` — Hook symbols: `use<Name>`
- Service files: `<name>.ts` — Service functions: camelCase → `fetchUsers`
- Util files: `<name>.ts` — Util functions: camelCase → `formatDate`
- Story files: `<name>.stories.ts` or `<name>.stories.tsx`

Rationale: Linux filesystems (CI/CD) are case-sensitive. kebab-case prevents file resolution bugs between Linux and macOS/Windows environments.

---

## Component Model: Colocated Smart Components

Each view is a **single file** (`<view>.view.tsx`) that handles data fetching, mutations, and rendering together. There is no separate `*.ui.tsx` counterpart — the view/ui split is not used in this project.

Sub-components that belong to a single view live in `views/<view>/components/` and can also fetch their own data via React Query (queries are deduplicated automatically). Sub-components shared across two or more views move to `src/components/`.

### Display-only sub-components (`src/components/`, `views/*/components/`)

Pure rendering components (charts, tables, calendars, form inputs) that only receive data via props and have no side effects. These are the only components that keep strict prop-driven boundaries.

```tsx
// ✅ A display-only chart sub-component
const FiberChart = ({ data }: { data: DailyFiberPoint[] }) => (
    <ResponsiveContainer>...</ResponsiveContainer>
);
```

### Views (`<view>.view.tsx`)

A view file owns everything: fetching, mutations, state, and rendering. No prop-drilling through an intermediate UI layer.

```tsx
// ✅ homescreen.view.tsx — data + rendering in one place
export const HomescreenView = () => {
    const { data } = useUsersQuery();
    const users = data?.users ?? [];

    return (
        <main className="main">
            <UserList users={users} />
        </main>
    );
};
```

```tsx
// ❌ DO NOT split into view + ui files
// homescreen.view.tsx → passes props to HomescreenUI
// homescreen.ui.tsx   → receives props, renders
// This creates prop drilling with no benefit when using React Query.
```

